<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<Pathway xmlns="http://pathvisio.org/GPML/2013a" Name="Oxidative stress response" Data-Source="WikiPathways" Version="20260722132145" Author="[MadhushriMSV, Egonw]" Last-Modified="20260722132145" Organism="Gadus morhua">
  <Comment Source="WikiPathways-description">Oxidative stress represents an imbalance between the production and manifestation of reactive oxygen species and a biological system's ability to readily detoxify the reactive intermediates or to repair the resulting damage. Disturbances in the normal redox state of tissues can cause toxic effects through the production of peroxides and free radicals that damage all components of the cell, including proteins, lipids, and DNA. Some reactive oxidative species can even act as messengers through a phenomenon called redox signaling. In humans and other vetebrates such as fish, oxidative stress is involved in many diseases. This pathway was inferred from  Danio rerio pathway Dr_Oxidative_stress_response_WP1372_20250227.gpmL. Proteins on this pathway were identified in Gadus morhua using data from FairdomHub repository: [10.15490/fairdomhub.1.study.753.2](https://doi.org/10.15490/fairdomhub.1.study.753.2).</Comment>
  <Comment Source="HomologyConvert">This pathway was inferred from Homo sapiens pathway [http://www.wikipathways.org/index.php?title=Pathway:WP408&amp;amp;amp;amp;oldid=21540 WP408(r21540)] with a 58% conversion rate.</Comment>
  <Comment Source="ECO">ECO:0007481 - biological system reconstruction evidence based on orthology evidence used in automatic assertion</Comment>
  <Comment Source="HomologyMapper">This pathway was inferred from Danio rerio pathway Dr_Oxidative_stress_response_WP1372_20250227.gpml.gpml (WP1372_r137017) with a 77.0% conversion rate.</Comment>
